Extended Data Fig. 9 | Inhibition of AMPK mitigates the effect of exendin-4 
on APP processing in vivo. AD mice were treated with exendin-4 with or 
without compound C to inhibit AMPK activity. Hemi-brains from the mice were 
homogenized in RIPA-Doc lysis buffer and separated with 8% Tris-glycine or 16% 
Tris-tricine SDS-PAGE. Full-length APP, APP CTFs (C99) and endogenous BACE1 
levels in the cortex (a and b) and the hippocampus (e and f) were detected. 
β-Actin was detected by anti-actin antibody AC-15 as the internal control.  
n = 3 independent experiments; One-way ANOVA followed by Tukey’s multiple 
comparisons test was performed for statistical analysis. ELISA was performed 
to measure Aβ40 and Aβ42 levels in the cortex (c) and the hippocampus (g). 
n = 3 independent experiments; One-way ANOVA followed by Tukey’s multiple 
comparisons test was performed for statistical analysis. Total RNA was isolated 
from mouse cortices and hippocampi. Sets of gene-specific primers were used 
to amplify App and Bace1 genes. qPCR was performed to measure mRNA levels 
of APP and BACE1 in the cortex (d) and the hippocampus (h). β-Actin was used 
as an internal control. n = 4 for each group; One-way ANOVA followed by Tukey’s 
multiple comparisons test was performed for statistical analysis. All the results 
are expressed as mean ± s.e.m. APP: β-amyloid precursor protein, Aβ: Amyloid 
β protein, BACE1: beta site APP cleaving enzyme 1, C.C: compound C, EX-4: 
exendin-4.
